# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fleming-cottage-hospital
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Plans for the complex were announced in 2010.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The facility, which cost £15 million to construct, opened in December 2013.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] It was the first healthcare facility to be completed in Scotland under the hub framework of the Scottish Futures Trust.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village, which is designed to offer services to 700 patients a day, contains 275 rooms including three dental suites, two minor procedure rooms and 29 consulting rooms.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Services being run from the health village include: cardiac rehabilitation, dentistry, dietetics, physiotherapy, podiatry, radiology, sexual health, speech and language therapy and minor surgery.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] An endoscopy service was provided from June 2014.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village acts as an educational resource for patients, carers and community-based staff.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village also provides improved access to community based learning opportunities for healthcare professionals such as general practitioners (GPs) and GP trainees.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Work on a mural on the side of the building began in July 2021.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] It is being painted by Fanakapan, a London-based artist, as part of the 2021 NuArt Festival.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital has its origins in the a small facility established at Guestrow in 1870.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] It moved to Barrett's Close in 1893 and to Castle Street in 1900.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The move to a new building, which was designed by James Brown Nicol and built between 1934 and 1937, formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by Professor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] An ante-natal hospital was added in 1941 and the facility joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital progressed to stage two accreditation of the Baby Friendly Hospital Initiative in July 2011.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Construction of new hospital buildings - for The Baird Family Hospital and Anchor cancer centre - was delayed after costs escalated from £163m to £223m.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] In February 2020, forecast completion dates were 2022 and March 2023 respectively.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The Department of Obstetrics and Gynaecology, University of Aberdeen, is based at the hospital, which conducts a variety of research with an emphasis on obstetric epidemiology (including maternal mortality and morbidity), infertility and the prevention of cancer in women.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Aberdeen is also particularly known for its research into multiple pregnancy.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The associated **Dugald Baird Centre for Research on Women's Health** was set up in 1995 and is primarily a research unit, with consultative and teaching responsibilities.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Current work focuses on a number of themes in reproductive health research and methodological development in evaluation.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The centre is named after Sir Dugald Baird (1899–1986), Regius Professor of Midwifery at the University of Aberdeen from 1937 to 1965.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The **Aberdeen Royal Infirmary** (**ARI**) is the largest hospital in the Grampian area, located on the Foresterhill site in Aberdeen, Scotland.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI is a teaching hospital offering tertiary care for a population of over 600,000 across the north-east of Scotland.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] It offers all medical specialities with the exception of heart and liver transplants.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Aberdeen Royal Infirmary has it origins in a facility established at Woolmanhill in 1739.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The move to the current site formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by the Scottish doctor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The granite buildings on the site were designed by James Brown Nicol.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital was officially opened by the Duke and Duchess of York on 23 September 1936—King Edward VIII had been due to open the infirmary but he called off his visit and instead went to Ballater railway station to meet the American socialite Wallis Simpson off her train.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The first patients were admitted a month later.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In the 1980s the English physicist John Mallard led a team which built the first whole body magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scanner.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The world's first whole-body MRI scanner was used for diagnostic imaging between 1980 and 1983.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The prototype machine, Mark One, was put on display in the hospital's art gallery in February 2016.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Following fundraising by *Evening Express* readers, in 1992 a Siemens scanner costing £870,000 was brought.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1984, a hyperbaric oxygen unit was built for the treatment of decompression illness and the hospital's in vitro fertilisation unit achieved a number of successful pregnancies in 1985, its first year of operation.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1986, a new £550,000 out-patient eye clinic opened, offering corrective laser eye surgery, and in 1989, the hospital introduced a breast cancer screening service for women over the age of 50, with X-rays taken every three years.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2013, a £110m emergency care centre development was completed.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] This was the first time that the Foresterhill campus had hosted emergency and urgent care facilities in the same building, and 75% of the beds in the centre are single-occupancy.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In February 2014, it was revealed that the hospital has a repairs backlog of £60 million.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] On 26 June 2014, John Swinney, the then Finance Secretary, announced a £120 million investment for a new cancer centre and maternity hospital on the site.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2016, the ARI became one of four major trauma centres as part of a national major trauma network in Scotland.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Social workers can be contacted in the hospital, and a branch of the Citizens Advice Bureau is based there.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by the volunteer-run radio station, Grampian Hospital Radio.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by several bus services with regular connections to Aberdeen city centre and service to places as far as Inverurie and Oldmeldrum in the north, Inverness in the West and Cove Bay in the south.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new multistorey carpark with space for over 1,000 cars was opened in 2017.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] There are close links with the University of Aberdeen's medical school and there has been pioneering research in many fields, including the development of MRI and positron emission tomography (PET) scanning.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new PET scanner was installed in 2006.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI has been one of the centres evaluating telemedicine equipment and developing services in Scotland.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Academy of Medical Royal Colleges and Faculties in Scotland produced a report entitled "Learning from serious failings in care" in July 2015.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The investigation was launched after scandals in the health service in 2013 and 2014 leading to concerns about patient safety and care at the infirmary.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] They found leadership and accountability were often lacking and bullying was endemic.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The 20 recommendations for improvements in the NHS included a set of minimum safe staffing levels for consultants, doctors, nurses and other staff in hospital settings.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] Aberlour, recorded in 1226 as *Aberlower*, means 'confluence of the Lour burn'.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] The first element is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth, confluence'.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] The name of the Lour burn is from Gaelic *labhar* 'loud, noisy'.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] This probably replaced an earlier Pictish cognate word.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] Charlestown refers to Charles Grant of Elchies.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] A site noted as Abirlaur is shown in this location on maps in Joan Blaeu's Atlas of Scotland, from 1654.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] The current village, Charlestown of Aberlour, was "founded by Charles Grant of Elchies in 1812 – with the name of Charlestown of Aberlour after his son Charles." It is commonly referred to simply as Aberlour.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] A grant of land from Charles Grant senior feued 100 plots along the south bank of the river and saw the start of the High Street (formerly Main Street) and parish church.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] The three locations are close enough in definition for there to be little distinction between them.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] The village was granted its feu charter in 1814 and began to operate its own markets.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] Whisky was a major industry even then and once the 1823 Excise Act was passed and a longer warehousing process introduced it began to take on the more mature characteristics that are familiar today.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] The first Aberlour distillery was established shortly after the Act became law, by the owner of a gentleman's estate where Aberlour House is situated.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] Soon after the property changed hands, that distillery was demolished.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] In 1879, local resident James Fleming (1830-1895, built a new Aberlour distillery alongside the Lour Burn; which is now owned and operated by the Pernod Ricard group of companies.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] Aberlour once was the site of an orphanage which was founded in 1875 by Margaret Macpherson Grant and a minister called Charles Jupp.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] His tomb lies in St Margaret's Episcopal Church which was the church used by the children of the orphanage.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] The orphanage was split into two separate units – one for the girls and the other for the boys.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] Between the two buildings was the school where the children were taught.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] Haynes and her twin brother Leonard spent four years, from 1929 to 1933, in Aberlour Orphanage; her experiences are recounted in her 1973 memoir *Haste Ye Back*.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] Aberlour Child Care Trust is now one of Scotland's main children's charities with services throughout Scotland.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] The Trust was also found to be a child care institution where children suffered physical, emotional and sexual abuse at the Scottish Child Abuse Inquiry in 2021.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] Aberlour is also the place where the famous Walkers shortbread is made.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] Walkers own the woods behind the factory – Fisherton woods.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] Until 2004, Aberlour House was the site of a school, a prep school for Gordonstoun; it is now offices for Walkers.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] Aberlour Golf Club (now defunct) first appeared in 1905 and continued until the late 1930s.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] Thomas Telford, the renowned civil engineer designed Craigellachie Bridge spanning the River Spey about 2 miles (3 km) to the north of the village.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] It was built after the Great Spate in the 19th century destroyed an earlier bridge.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] Alexander Cameron Sim, a pharmacist who introduced lemonade (locally called ramune) to Japan, was born in the village.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aberlour] The area was once served by Aberlour railway station, but this closed on 18 October 1965 as a result of the Beeching Axe.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aboyne-hospital] The facility, which was designed by Jenkins & Marr, opened as an infectious diseases hospital in 1898.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aboyne-hospital] A ward pavilion was added in 1926 and, after the hospital had joined the National Health Service in 1948, a new health centre was added in 1980.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/aboyne-hospital] A major refurbishment started in 2002 and the newly modernised facilities were opened by Anne, Princess Royal in August 2003.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Chalmers Hospital was founded by Alexander Chalmers (died 11 August 1835), a merchant of Banff, who left the whole of his estate to be applied, upon the death of his wife, towards funding and building a hospital for the people in the Royal Burgh of Banff.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Mrs Chalmers died in 1861, and Chalmers Hospital opened on 19 July 1864.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The original 'deed of mortification' set out that this was for any destitute sick persons born, domiciled or resident in the Banff area, although in 1929 the trustees successfully petitioned for the removal of this restriction.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Some major redevelopment work began in October 2008, after the hospital attracted criticism for not being up to date, with some of the interior features having been there since the Second World War.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The hospital remained open during the work, although the Findlater ward services were moved to Campbell Hospital in Portsoy until the Findlater ward was refurbished, and Seafield and Deveron ward were merged.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The midwifery unit was demolished and rebuilt to provide modern facilities.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Numerous other internal changes were also made inside, including X-ray facilities being moved to a different area of the building.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The redevelopment also provided upgraded facilities for physiotherapy, occupational therapy, speech and language therapy and podiatry.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The completion of the redevelopment was recognised with a visit by the Princess Royal in March 2012.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The hospital is supported by GPs from Banff, Gamrie, Deveron, Macduff, Portsoy and Aberchirder Medical Practices.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/city-hospital-aberdeen] The facility, which was designed by William Smith, was established as an infectious diseases hospital in 1874.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/city-hospital-aberdeen] It was significantly expanded in 1895 and a new nurses' home was completed in 1931.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/city-hospital-aberdeen] During the 1964 Aberdeen typhoid outbreak, over 400 cases were diagnosed and the patients were quarantined at the City Hospital and Woodend Hospital, although no fatalities resulted.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] The hospital was financed by a legacy from **James Fleming** (1830-1895), the distiller, and designed by James Leslie Findlay.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] In 1891 the County Medical Officer for Banff reported: "The central portion of the District, including the parishes of Mortlach and **Aberlour**, with the police Burgh of Dufftown, is without Hospital accommodation for infectious diseases.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] I am of opinion that a combination between these Parishes for providing such accommodation would be advisable, or even a larger scheme to embrace the Parish of Knockando, and perhaps the Parish and Burgh of Rothes in Elginshire might be still better.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] In the remaining and upper part of this District, embracing Cabrach, Inveravon, Glenlivet, Kirkmichael, and Tomintoul, the population (except in the Village of Tomintoul) is sparse and scattered - distances are great and means of transport not readily available.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] Since the Notification Act was adopted only three cases have been reported from this part of the District, viz., one of Erysipelas and two of Typhoid Fever, one of the latter being an imported case.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] In conclusion, I would beg to quote the following from the Memorandum issued by the Local Government Board *"On the provision of Isolation Hospital Accommodation."* - Large villages and groups of adjacent villages will commonly require the same sort of provisions as towns.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] "In our last we referred briefly to a bequest by the late Mr.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] James Fleming, Aberlour, for erecting and endowing an hospital.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] We have since learned some precise particulars respecting the bequest.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] By a deed of mortification, dated April 6 1895, Mr.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] Fleming, in order to benefit sick poor and others in the parishes of Aberlour, Inveravon, and Knockando, made over to trustees the sum of £8,000 to secure the necessary ground at Aberlour, and building thereon a Cottage Hospital, to be called the Fleming Cottage Hospital".
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] James Thomson, in his 1902 book *Recollections of a Speyside Parish* commented: "It is hardly possible for the younger portion of the inhabitants to fully realise the changed conditions that they are now enjoying.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] These changed conditions have been mainly brought about by the liberality of men who, by the wise disposal of their means, have benefited the parish, and laid the inhabitants under an everlasting debt of gratitude to its benefactors.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] Fleming, whose benefactions to the place and to the people are wisely bestowed on objects that will be of lasting and real benefit to the parish.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] The hospital that has been built and endowed by his liberality will always remain a memorial to his Christian philanthropy.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] I can well remember more than one epidemic that devastated many a home in the village. had there been at the time such an institution the place many lives might have been saved.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] The Fleming Cottage Hospital was officially opened on Monday 30 April 1900, by Mr.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] John Findlay of Aberlour in the presence of a large company of ladies and gentlemen.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] The ceremony took place shortly after twelve o'clock and was followed by a cake and wine banquet in The Fleming Hall.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] Fleming Hospital was purpose built and is physically adjoined to the local health centre providing GP, community nursing and other primary care services.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] It has 15 beds providing medical care, rehabilitation, assessment, palliative/terminal care, convalescence and respite care.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] The hospital also has a minor injuries unit, which is open 24 hours a day.
[src:fleming-cottage-hospital/fleming-cottage-hospital] General medical and surgical out patient clinics are held on site.
